<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Bash on Jared Szajkowski</title><link>https://www.jaredszajkowski.com/tags/bash/</link><description>Recent content in Bash on Jared Szajkowski</description><generator>Hugo -- gohugo.io</generator><language>en-us</language><lastBuildDate>Mon, 23 Sep 2024 00:00:00 +0000</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://www.jaredszajkowski.com/tags/bash/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Simple Incremental Bash Backup Script</title><link>https://www.jaredszajkowski.com/2024/01/12/simple-incremental-bash-backup-script/</link><pubDate>Fri, 12 Jan 2024 00:00:01 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://www.jaredszajkowski.com/2024/01/12/simple-incremental-bash-backup-script/</guid><description>&lt;img src="https://www.jaredszajkowski.com/2024/01/12/simple-incremental-bash-backup-script/cover.jpg" alt="Featured image of post Simple Incremental Bash Backup Script" />&lt;h2 id="introduction">Introduction
&lt;/h2>&lt;p>While there are &lt;a class="link" href="https://wiki.archlinux.org/title/Synchronization_and_backup_programs" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>numerous backup solutions available for Linux&lt;/a>, many require extensive configuration and maintenance, and restoring from the backup is not always simple. Incremental backups are ideal because they maintain snapshots of the files and allow for access to previous versions of files.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Linux Journal recently &lt;a class="link" href="https://www.linuxjournal.com/content/exploring-rsync-tar-and-other-backup-solutions" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>published an article on various backup solutions&lt;/a>, and I thought I&amp;rsquo;d provide my incremental backup script that uses &lt;code>rsync&lt;/code> and &lt;code>cp&lt;/code>.&lt;/p>
&lt;h2 id="incremental-backup-script">Incremental backup script
&lt;/h2>&lt;p>This script provides an incremental backup solution and only requires &lt;code>rsync&lt;/code> and &lt;code>cp&lt;/code> to be installed on the system.&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div class="chroma">
&lt;table class="lntable">&lt;tr>&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code>&lt;span class="lnt"> 1
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt"> 2
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt"> 3
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt"> 4
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt"> 5
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt"> 6
